"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964047","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK’s FinTech Bridge agreements have facilitated positive cross border activity between the UK and our Bridge partner markets, and UK officials work closely with counterparts in each FinTech Bridge market to support firms seeking to export internationally.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","169237 ; 169238 ; 169239 ; 169240","2018-09-10T14:39:34.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964047/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964047/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Financial Services: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the FinTech bridge agreement between the UK and China.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","169241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964048","Treasury","false","2018-09-11","<p>UK and US government officials and regulators continue to engage on a range of financial services policy, including FinTech. There are no current plans for a UK-US FinTech Bridge.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-09-11T16:03:18.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964048/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964048/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Financial Services: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has had discussions with the US Administration on establishing a FinTech bridge agreement between the UK and the USA.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","169242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964049","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>There have been no recent discussions between the Chancellor of the Exchequer and international counterparts on establishing new FinTech Bridge agreements since the signing of the UK-Australia FinTech Bridge in March 2018. However the UK remains committed to fostering international collaboration and exploring the scope for additional FinTech Bridge agreements where opportunities are present.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-09-10T15:01:59.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964049/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964049/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has had discussions with his international counterparts on establishing new Fin Tech bridge agreements between their countries and the UK.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","169243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964050","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Chancellor has not had any formal discussions with the Bank of England about a state-backed digital currency. Whilst the Bank of England is not planning to create a central bank-issued digital currency, it has been carrying out research to understand any potential implications. For more information on this research, please visit this page: <a href="https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/research/digital-currencies" target="_blank">https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/research/digital-currencies</a></p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-09-10T15:03:01.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964050/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964050/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Cryptocurrencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has had discussions with the Bank of England on the establishment of a state-backed digital currency.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","169244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964051","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) does not hold this information in the format requested for military personnel.</p><p>The number of MOD civilian personnel within MOD Main Top Level Budgetary areas identified as administrative support as at 1 April 2018 was 4,703. This does not include Trading Fund organisations, the Defence Equipment and Support Bespoke Trading Entity, locally engaged civilians, and Royal Fleet Auxiliary personnel.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-09-11T16:14:06.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964051/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964051/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-03","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 15 of his Department’s Annual Report and Accounts 2017-18, how many (a) military and (b) civilian personnel in his Department perform an administrative role.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","169195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964052","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-09-11","<p>Project Centurion is due to deliver transition of Attack capability from Tornado GR4 to Typhoon by 31 December 2018, ahead of Tornado GR4 reaching its out of service date of 31 March 2019.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-09-11T16:41:34.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964052/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964052/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-03","European Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 16 of his Department’s Annual Report and Accounts 2017-18, what the timetable is for the completion of Project Centurion.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","169196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964053","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-09-10","<p>Significant infrastructure work is being undertaken at RAF Marham to support the F-35, including the development of new squadron, training and maintenance facilities and the refurbishment of much of the airfield operating surfaces. A significant amount of this work was completed in preparation for the arrival of the first Lightning F35-B aircraft in June 2018. The majority of the remaining work at RAF Marham will be completed later this year and the final element is scheduled for completion in 2023. The estimated cost for this work is £550 million.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-09-10T15:35:01.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964053/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964053/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-03","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 16 of his Department’s Annual Report and Accounts 2017-18, what infrastructure work is being carried out at RAF Marham to support the arrival of the F-35s; what the timetable is for the completion of that work; and what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of that work.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","169197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964054","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-09-11","<p>The over 30 operations referred to in the Department's Annual Report and Accounts include:</p><p>BACKWELL</p><p>BRANTA</p><p>CABRIT</p><p>CATAN</p><p>CROSSWAYS</p><p>ELGIN</p><p>FAIRFIELD</p><p>HALLEX</p><p>INVOKER</p><p>KIPION</p><p>LITTEN</p><p>MANSIO</p><p>METRO</p><p>MODEST</p><p>MONOGRAM</p><p>NEWCOMBE</p><p>ORBITAL</p><p>RECOMPOSE</p><p>PANAKA</p><p>PERCIVAL</p><p>PRAISER</p><p>PRESIDIUM</p><p>SHADER</p><p>TAILPIN</p><p>TANGHAM</p><p>TORAL</p><p>TOSCA</p><p>TRAMAL</p><p>TRENTON</p><p>TURUS</p><p>VOGUL</p><p>The countries referred to in the Department's Annual Report and Accounts include:</p><p>Afghanistan</p><p>Bahrain</p><p>Bosnia and Herzegovina</p><p>Columbia</p><p>Cyprus</p><p>Democratic Republic of Congo</p><p>Egypt</p><p>Estonia</p><p>Iraq</p><p>Italy</p><p>Jordan</p><p>Kenya</p><p>Kingdom of Saudi Arabia</p><p>Kosovo</p><p>Kuwait</p><p>Libya</p><p>Mali</p><p>Niger</p><p>Nigeria</p><p>Pakistan</p><p>Poland</p><p>Somalia</p><p>South Sudan</p><p>Ukraine</p><p>United Arab Emirates</p><p>Some operational names and locations have been excluded for operational security. Changes in operational circumstances and the strategic environment affect where UK Armed Forces personnel are deployed.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-09-11T15:08:50.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964054/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964054/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-03","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 22 of his Department’s Annual Report and Accounts 2017-18, what the (a) 30 operations and (b) 25 countries are in which UK armed forces personnel are deployed.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","169198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964055","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>Data on the take up rates of the health check of children aged two years undertaken by health visitors is only available at local authority level. Data on take-up rates by levels of household income of recipients of the health check for children aged two years undertaken by health visitors is not collected. Therefore, no direct comparison can be made between household income and uptake of service.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-09-11T16:11:07.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964055/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964055/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of take-up rates by levels of household income of recipients of the health check for children aged two years undertaken by health visitors.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","169035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964056","Treasury","false","2018-09-06","<p>Statistics relating to the policy to provide support for a maximum of two children in Child Tax Credit were published on 28th June 2018 and can be accessed at <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719458/Two_children_and_exceptions_in_tax_credits_and_Universal_Credit_April_2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719458/Two_children_and_exceptions_in_tax_credits_and_Universal_Credit_April_2018.pdf</a>.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-09-06T12:52:23.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964056/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964056/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many NCC1, Support for a child conceived without your consent forms have been received by HMRC.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","169454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964057","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The information required to answer this question is not currently held centrally by the Joint Funds Unit for the Prosperity Fund and cannot be collated accurately in the time available, or at reasonable cost. In line with transparency policies, departments delivering Prosperity Fund programmes routinely publish business cases including financial and commercial information once approved.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-09-06T15:45:39.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964057/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964057/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-03","Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if his Department will provide a list of the third-party organisations that have received funding from the Prosperity Fund in the the last 12 months to design or implement projects overseas.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","168997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964058","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>NHS England is committed to reducing health inequalities, and respiratory disease will be a clinical priority in the National Health Service long-term plan.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence shows that disadvantaged groups and areas of deprivation experience higher incidence rates of respiratory disease (such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma). This is in part due to higher levels of smoking, exposure to higher levels of air pollution, poor housing conditions, early life experiences and exposure to occupational hazards.</p><p> </p><p>National programmes such as the Elective Care Programme, NHS RightCare and Getting It Right First Time are focussing on respiratory disease management and have outlined the benefits that improvements in this area can bring to patients.</p><p> </p><p>Cancer of the larynx and lung are more common in the 20% most deprived patients relative to the 20% more well off patients. Smoking and increased alcohol consumption, both risk factors for these cancers, are also more common amongst more deprived populations.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is to pilot low dose CT scanning for lung cancer, focussing on those clinical commissioning groups with the highest lung cancer mortality and incidence. These pilots, together with the implementation of rapid diagnosis pathways for lung cancer will help to close the gap in inequalities.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-09-11T16:00:27.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964058/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964058/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Respiratory System: Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the potential causal link between respiratory diseases and deprivation and its effect on levels of (a) chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, (b) cancer, (c) tuberculosis, (d) pneumonia, (e) pulmonary fibrosis and (f) asthma; and what steps he is taking to reduce any such inequalities relating to respiratory diseases.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","169538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964059","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-09-13","<p>The UK is seeking the best possible arrangements for the broadcasting sector. We are focussing on ensuring the ability to trade as freely as possible with the EU and supporting the continued growth of the UK and European broadcasting industry. In addition, due to the UK's ongoing participation in the Council of Europe's Convention on Transfrontier Television (CTT), which will not be affected by the UK’s withdrawal from the EU, works originating in the UK will continue to be classed as European Works, which is extremely important to industry.</p><p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of continuing analysis in support of our EU exit negotiations and preparations. This analysis will help define our future partnership with the EU, and informs our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.<br><br>Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that would reveal our negotiating position and so the Government will not provide an ongoing commentary on internal analytical work.</p><p>The Government has confirmed that when we bring forward the vote on the final deal, we will ensure that Parliament is presented with the appropriate analysis to make an informed decision.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-09-13T08:59:07.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964059/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964059/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-09-03","Broadcasting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 24 July 2018 to Question 165184 on Brexit, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect of the Government's policies on the future relationship between the UK and the EU on (a) jobs in and (b) value of the broadcasting sector in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","169859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964060","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-11","<p>The West Coast Main Line (WCML) Franchise was let by the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising (OPRAF), a non-Departmental government body following a competition to Virgin Rail Group<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> (VRG). VRG, through a competitive process, procured both rolling stock and the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions. West Coast Train Care, an Alstom company, took over responsibility for the Depots and Maintenance of all trains and the existing staff in the Depot. This was all included in VRG’s franchise bid for the WCML in 1997 thus the costs of this separation rested with the operator, while the taxpayer benefitted as a whole from the returns of the new 15 year franchise awarded.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>At the time of the WCML franchise award in 1997, the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising (OPRAF) procurement rules and procedures were followed. OPRAF, will have scrutinised bidder responses under the parameters set out in the ITT, including the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions.</p><p> </p><p>The Franchisee (Virgin Rail Group) was responsible for compliance with the Railways Act 1993 in transferring employees from the operator to the maintainer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> In its original entity – i.e. excluding Stagecoach</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","169785","2018-09-11T11:46:01.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964060/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-03","West Coast Partnership Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department agreed to the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions relating to the West Coast Trains Limited franchise; whether his Department undertook at competitive tender relating to that separation of functions; and whether funds accrued to the public purse as a result of that separation of functions. .","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964061","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-11","<p>The West Coast Main Line (WCML) Franchise was let by the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising (OPRAF), a non-Departmental government body following a competition to Virgin Rail Group<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> (VRG). VRG, through a competitive process, procured both rolling stock and the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions. West Coast Train Care, an Alstom company, took over responsibility for the Depots and Maintenance of all trains and the existing staff in the Depot. This was all included in VRG’s franchise bid for the WCML in 1997 thus the costs of this separation rested with the operator, while the taxpayer benefitted as a whole from the returns of the new 15 year franchise awarded.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>At the time of the WCML franchise award in 1997, the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising (OPRAF) procurement rules and procedures were followed. OPRAF, will have scrutinised bidder responses under the parameters set out in the ITT, including the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions.</p><p> </p><p>The Franchisee (Virgin Rail Group) was responsible for compliance with the Railways Act 1993 in transferring employees from the operator to the maintainer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> In its original entity – i.e. excluding Stagecoach</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","169784","2018-09-11T11:46:01.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964061/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964061/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-03","West Coast Partnership Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the separation of the fleet maintenance and engineering functions relating to the West Coast Trains Limited franchise, whether (a) assets were fully scrutinised and valued in relation to that separation of functions and (b) the pension funds of employees affected by that separation of functions received protections under the terms of the Railways Act 1993.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964062","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Social Housing Green Paper was published on 14 August, with 12 weeks for consultation. While the Government was committed to publishing the Green Paper as soon as possible, it was important that we took the time to ensure that the proposed options did justice to the complex and challenging issues that we are seeking to remedy. As the Government continued to receive representations during recess asking to see the Green Paper issued without delay, it did not seem right to artificially hold up publication until Parliament returned.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-09-11T15:15:13.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964062/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964062/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-03","Social Rented Housing: Consultation Papers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for publishing the social housing green paper; and for what reasons that green paper was not published prior to the House rising for summer recess.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","169518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964063","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA)’s decision to set a deadline for mis-sold Payment Protection Insurance (PPI) was announced in August 2017, and gives consumers two years to make a claim. The government is confident in the FCA’s approach to handling mis-sold PPI and the deadline was set by the FCA in their role as an independent regulator. For this reason, the Chancellor is unable to review the deadline.</p><p> </p><p>The deadline was set to prompt consumers to complain or check whether they had PPI. It is intended to help consumers get redress sooner, improve the efficiency of PPI complaints handling, and bring the PPI issue to an orderly conclusion to rebuild trust in the retail banking sector.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA will write to Laura Smith MP to set out their position in more detail.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-09-10T14:36:44.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964063/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Insurance: Misrepresentation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the estimated £70 billion in unpaid compensation for the mis-selling of payment protection insurance, if he will review the deadline for making a compensation claim.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964064","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA)’s decision to set a deadline for mis-sold Payment Protection Insurance (PPI) was announced in August 2017, and gives consumers two years to make a claim. The government is confident in the FCA’s approach to handling mis-sold PPI and the deadline was set by the FCA in their role as an independent regulator. As this was an FCA decision and not legislation, the Chancellor has not made an assessment on the impacts on the court system resulting from the deadline.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-09-10T14:59:27.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964064/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Insurance: Misrepresentation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an assessment of the potential increase in demand on the court system as a result of the deadline for making PPI claims via the Financial Ombudsman; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964065","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-09-06","<p>The implementation planning underway will determine what the £825,000 of income for investment in the Sunderland Magistrates’ Court will be spent on. The appropriate budget allocation for these funds will be determined at the conclusion of this planning.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-09-06T15:34:06.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964065/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964065/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-03","Magistrates' Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 24 July 2018 to Question 166155, to which budget headlines will the £825,000 of income for reinvestment in the Sunderland Magistrates’ court be allocated.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964066","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) recognises that myalgic encephalomyelitis (ME) is a debilitating condition. The NIHR is speaking with the Chronic Fatigue Syndrome/ME Research Collaborative and patient representatives about how best we can support a joined up approach to high quality research into this complex disorder.</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR welcomes funding applications for research into any aspect of human health, including ME; it is not usual practice to ring-fence funds for particular topics or conditions. Applications are subject to peer review and judged in open competition, with awards being made on the basis of the importance of the topic to patients and health and care services, value for money and scientific quality.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-09-11T13:55:58.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964066/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964066/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to support biomedical research on myalgic encephalomyelitis.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","169455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964067","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-09-11","<p>Security personnel are not employed to assist with the administrative processing of tribunal cases; this is undertaken by dedicated administrative staff.</p><p> </p><p>Contracted security personnel are, however, deployed to ensure the security and safety of all persons who work in and attend tribunal premises, and undertake specific duties including searching the public on entry and responding to security incidents. They are not involved in any administrative process outside of those duties.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-09-11T13:09:58.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964067/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964067/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-03","HM Courts and Tribunals Service: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the HM Courts and Tribunals Service employ security personnel to assist with the processing of tribunal cases.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","169517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964068","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-09-06","<p>HMCTS is committed to investing in the court estate in the city of Sunderland and will spend over £5m during the next ten years on upgrading and maintaining the current magistrates’ court.</p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-09-06T15:31:46.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964068/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964068/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-03","Magistrates' Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department plans to spend on upgrading Sunderland Magistrates Court.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964069","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>Health Education England (HEE) made 2,605 midwifery training places available in England in the 2016-17 academic year, with 2,602 of these places filled. The reforms for healthcare education funding from August 2017 mean students have moved onto the student loans system for 2017-18; giving universities the flexibility to provide additional places, based on local need and National Health Service clinical capacity. Health Education England will continue to fund the required number of clinical placements to meet the longer-term NHS workforce needs. Based on the latest un-validated data HEE expect 2,692 training places to be filled in England in 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to increasing the number of available midwifery training places in England by more than 3,000 over a four year period from 2019. The increase in available places will start in the 2019 academic year, with an additional 650 training places with increases of 1,000 in the subsequent years.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-09-11T11:03:21.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964069/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964069/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many training places for midwifery were (a) commissioned and (b) filled in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","169176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964070","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>The total numbers of midwives in training in England as at 31 March 2017 was 6,559. Data on the number of midwives in training in 2018 is not yet available.</p><p>The Government has committed to increasing the number of available midwifery training places in England by more than 3,000 over a four year period from 2019. The increase in available places will start in the 2019 academic year, with an additional 650 training places with increases of 1,000 in the subsequent years.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-09-11T15:19:17.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964070/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964070/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the total number of midwives in training was in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","169177"
